      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're absolutely right to want the minimal fix, and while the old washer is the usual culprit, the valve body itself can sometimes be the source of trouble. Sometimes a tiny bit of mineral scale or debris gets stuck on the valve seat, preventing the washer from sealing properly even when it looks clean. You might also find that the stem isn't moving all the way down because of a slight bend or corrosion, which is why you should inspect the stem carefully before installing the new washer.\n\nIt's a bit like trying to fit a key into a lock that's been sitting in a damp, dusty corner for years; sometimes the metal just needs a little polishing or cleaning to work smoothly again. If you're feeling adventurous, you could try using a small brush or a bit of vinegar to scrub the seat area before replacing the washer, but be gentle so you don't scratch the metal.\n\nJust remember, if you're not comfortable working with plumbing tools, it might be worth calling a professional plumber, as they have the experience to spot any hidden issues that a DIYer might miss. After all, a little extra expertise can save you from accidentally breaking something more expensive than the faucet itself.",
